\chapter{Command-Line Interface}
\label{tutorial-cli}

The command-line interface has two jobs.  It must expose the standalone
[[tutorial]] command, and it must make that same functionality available
to other CLIs that want tutorials as a subcommand.

Typer is the primary interface because it keeps the standalone command
compact and gives structured help text with little boilerplate.
Argparse support is still important, though, because some host CLIs are
already built around it.  The implementation therefore shares one runner
layer and only varies the argument plumbing.


